A Deeper Dive Into John’s Hopkins Corona Database

The John’s Hopkins Novel Corona Virus (COVID-19) epidemiological data is compiled by the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering (JHU CCSE) from various sources.
The dataset contains data since 22nd of January 2020. For the data and more information about it, please visit here.

In this lab you will pick up where we left in lecture 2 and analyze the Corona cases and deaths data.

    To achieve the aggregation use the aggregate function. In addition, order the data-frame first by Country and then by Date (increasing order). The columns of each of the two resulting data-frames should be Country.Region, Date, Value. (5pts)

#b
cases$Date=as.Date(cases$Date)
cases.agg1<-aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region+Date,data=cases,FUN=sum)
cases.agg<- cases.agg1[order(cases.agg1$Country.Region,cases.agg1$Date),]

dethes$Date=as.Date(dethes$Date)
deaths.agg1<-aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region+Date,data=dethes,FUN=sum)
deaths.agg<- deaths.agg1[order(deaths.agg1$Country.Region,deaths.agg1$Date),]

recoverd$Date=as.Date(recoverd$Date)
recovered.agg1<-aggregate(Value ~ Country.Region+Date,data=recoverd,FUN=sum)
recovered.agg<- recovered.agg1[order(recovered.agg1$Country.Region,recovered.agg1$Date),]

#c
acases<- cases %>% group_by(Country.Region,Date) %>% summarise(casesValue=sum(Value))
scases<-acases %>% inner_join (cases.agg,by=c("Country.Region","Date"),by.x="casesValue",by.y="value")

Q2

Analysis of Daily New Corona Cases and Deaths

20 points

The two datasets (Corona Cases and Deaths) register the value of cases and deaths, respectively, as a cumulative sum for each day. In this question we would like to understand the daily differences between consecutive days.

  1. Add a new column named Diff to both the cases.agg and the deaths.agg data-frames. This new column should register the daily Value difference for each country. In other words, the Diff column shows how many new cases/deaths each country incurs every day. Hint - diff must be per country. (7pts)
  2. Find the top 10 instances of country and date combinations with the greatest absolute number of new daily Corona cases and deaths (separately). Print the result in a descriptive format. (5pts)
  3. In one figure, plot Italy’s new daily Corona cases AND deaths as a function of Date. Choose the plot type you think that makes the most sense. (3pts)
  4. Plot the same graph as in (c), but this time plot the number of new cases on the logarithm scale. What can we learn? (5pts)

Solution:

YOUR SOLUTION HERE. Use code blocks and markdown to clearly communicate your work.

#a
cases.agg<-mutate(cases.agg,diff = 0   )
cases.agg$diff[1]<-cases.agg$Value[1]
i<-1
t<-17390
while (t>i) {
i=i+1
row<-cases.agg[i,]
prevrow<-cases.agg[i-1,]
if(prevrow[1]==row[1]){
newvalue<-row[3]-prevrow[3]  
}else{
newvalue<-cases.agg$Value[i]
}
cases.agg$diff[i]<-newvalue
}


deaths.agg<-mutate(deaths.agg,diff = 0   )
deaths.agg$diff[1]<-deaths.agg$Value[1]
i<-1
t<-17390
while (t>i) {
i=i+1
row<-deaths.agg[i,]
prevrow<-deaths.agg[i-1,]
if(prevrow[1]==row[1]){
newvalue=row[3]-prevrow[3]  
}else{
newvalue=deaths.agg$Value[i]
}
deaths.agg$diff[i]=newvalue
}

#c
italy<-cases.agg[which(cases.agg$Country.Region =='Italy'),] %>% inner_join (deaths.agg[which(deaths.agg$Country.Region =='Italy'),],by=c("Country.Region","Date"),)
  
plot(x=italy$Date, y= italy$diff.x,
    main= "italy daily number of sick and deaths", 
    xlab= "dates",
    ylab= "daily number",
    col= "blue")
points(x=italy$Date, y= italy$diff.y, 
    main= "italy", 
    xlab= "dates",
    ylab= "daily number",
    col= "red")
legend("topleft",c("sick","deaths"),fill=c("blue","red"))

#d
plot(x=italy$Date, y= log(italy$diff.x),
    main= ("italy daily log number of sick and number of deaths"), 
    xlab= "dates",
    ylab= "log number",
    col= "blue")
points(x=italy$Date, y= italy$diff.y, 
    main= "italy", 
    xlab= "dates",
    ylab= "daily number",
    col= "red")
legend("topleft",c("log sick","deaths"),fill=c("blue","red"))

#### Q2 answer In Q2.c we made a plot showing daily new corona cases (of people infected with the virus) and daily deaths. It shows that both curves grow exponentially, but the new cases (the blue curve, first plot) grow faster. In Q2.d we tried to have a better understanding of the differences between the 2 curves. In order to do so, we used a logarithmic scale. Now, as the death curve was flattened (red curve, second plot) we were able to see that the growth of new cases VS deaths (blue curve, second plot) is a concave curve which is still very high, but becomes more stable as time passes.



Q3

Preparing and Analyzing the World Bank Data

25 points

  1. Rename the columns of eco_data: country,S_country,feature,feature_code,Y2018V,Y2019V. (2pts)
  2. Create a new eco data-frame whose dimensions are \(N \times 11\), where N is the number of countries. The first column should include the names of the countries in eco_data.
    The rest of the columns should be the features with their respective values in eco_data for each country from 2018. Print the head of the new data-frame.(8pts).
    In other words, in this question you are asked to create a new eco data-frame whose dimensions are \(N \times 11\), where N is the number of countries (the first column should include the names of the countries in eco_data). The rest of the columns should be the features with their respective values in eco_data for each country from 2018. Print the head of the new data-frame. You may delete rows with NA as a country value only.
  3. Select and rename the following columns: country as country, GDP(US currency) as GDP, Population ages 65 and above (% of total population) as pop65, Population in the largest city (% of urban population) as pop_city_ratio, Population, total as pop_total columns . (2pts)
  4. Show a table of the five countries with the highest per capita GDP in 2018.
    Next (considering all countries), plot the % of population over 65 vs. log of GDP per capita in 2018, after excluding the 10% countries with the lowest GDP per capita. Using lm and abline, add a regression line to the plot. What is your conclusion? (13 pts)

Solution:

#loading the `eco_data`:
eco_data <- read.csv(url("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/DataScienceHU/DataAnalysisR_2020/master/data/economic_data.csv"))

eco_data <- rename(eco_data, country = Country.Name )
eco_data <- rename(eco_data, S_country = Country.Code )
eco_data <- rename(eco_data, feature = Series.Name )
eco_data <- rename(eco_data, feature_code = Series.Code )
eco_data <- rename(eco_data, Y2018V = X2018..YR2018. )
eco_data <- rename(eco_data, Y2019V = X2019..YR2019. )


eco_data_new <- eco_data[c(1:2640) , c(1,3,5) ]
eco_data_new$Y2018V <- as.numeric(as.character(eco_data_new$Y2018V)) 
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion

## 145      116639.89
## 146       87208.54
## 234       82796.55
## 181       81697.25
eco_data_new <- head(eco_data_new , as.integer(264*0.9))
plot(x= eco_data_new$pop65, 
     y= log(eco_data_new$GDP_per_capita) , 
     col = "black" , 
     main = "log GDP per capita VS % of olded population" ,
     ylab = "log GDP per capita" ,
     xlab = "%of olded population") 
abline(lm(log(eco_data_new$GDP_per_capita) ~ eco_data_new$pop65, data = eco_data_new) ,col="red")

#### Q3.d explanition The graph describes how GDP per capita changes in accordance with the precentage of older population per country, using logarithmic scale. The age for “older” was set to 65 and above, since this is the age for retirement in most countries. The log of the GDP per capita in this graph was chosen as it presents a relatively good perspective of the economy’s state of the countries. It can be learned from the plot that countries with higher GDP per capita can support any rate of older population, while in countries with a lower GDP per capita (less then 8) the rate of older population is 7% or less. This can be explained by the social idea that a country should support the older pepole who were mostly productive workers during their younger lives and are now retired. Countries with smaller GDP per capita might not be able to support their older population due to lack of economic stability and strength.



Q4

Joining the Datasets

20 points

  1. Join the deaths.agg, cases.agg, and recovered.agg into one data-frame called corona.(5pts)
  2. Join the corona and eco data-frames in a way that will keep the most information regarding the data (but not full join).
    Make sure that no essential data is thrown away (show this). (3pts)
  3. Create new columns of normalized cases, deaths, and recovered so they will show the number of cases per 100,000 people for each country.
    Using the last day of March as a reference, create a single stacked bar plot that visualizes the top 10 countries in terms of normalized Corona cases, and their respected normalized Corona deaths and recovered, as done in Q1.
    how is it different from the graph before normalization? (5pts)
  4. Using the last day of March as a reference, create a scatter-plot of normalized deaths and cases vs. pop65. Limit the plot to show only countries with 15% or more of pop65.
    In addition, color the outliers( pop65>24, norm100K_deaths>15) in that plot in red and add to the plot their country names (7pts)

Solution:

#a
corona<-cases.agg %>% inner_join (deaths.agg,by=c("Country.Region","Date"),) %>% rename(diffcases=diff.x , diffdeaths= diff.y , valuecases=Value.x ,valuedeaths=Value.y)
corona<-corona %>% inner_join (recovered.agg,by=c("Country.Region","Date"),)

#b
eco <- rename(eco, Country.Region = country )
eco$Country.Region<-as.character(eco$Country.Region)
corona$Country.Region<-as.character(corona$Country.Region)
ecocorona<-corona %>% left_join(eco,by="Country.Region")

#c
ecocorona<- ecocorona %>% mutate(sdcases=as.numeric(ecocorona$valuecases*100000/ecocorona$pop_total),sdeaths=as.numeric(ecocorona$valuedeaths*100000/ecocorona$pop_total),sdrecovered=as.numeric(ecocorona$Value*100000/ecocorona$pop_total))

ecocoronamarch <- ecocorona[which(ecocorona$Date == "2020-03-31"),]


chooseorder<-ecocoronamarch[order(ecocoronamarch$sdcases,decreasing =TRUE ),]
sdmarchtop10<-chooseorder[1:10,]

Q5

Open Question

10 points

Write an interesting research question regarding the Corona outbreak and then follow the steps to answer it using tables and plots. You can use the loaded datasets or any other dataset you find as long as you add the data file to your lab1 repository so it can be loaded directly from a url (e.g. the World Bank). This question will be graded based on creativity, originality, and the novelty of the analysis.

Solution:

This database is taken from the Israeli Ministry of Health. It includes data regarding people who recoverd from Coronavirus, such as age groups, gender, how many days passed from the first positive test to the negetive one, and the number of tests they went through in total. We chose to research the recovery time, and whether it depends on age or gender. In order to study it, we made 3 boxplots: one for the female group, one for the male group and the third showing the total for both together. The axes show the number of days which passed between the positive to the negetive test by age groups. As we can see, the plots show that the median is about the same for all age groups, which brings us to the conclusion that the healing period length does not distinctly depends on age. Notice that the variance of time for recovery is smaller in the male plot for all age groups.

tests_data <- read.csv('corona_recovered.csv')
tests_data$days_between_pos_and_neg <- as.numeric(tests_data$days_between_pos_and_neg)
tests_data <- subset(tests_data, days_between_pos_and_neg < 40 )
tests_data <- tests_data[order(tests_data$days_between_pos_and_neg, decreasing = TRUE),]

plot(tests_data$days_between_pos_and_neg ~ tests_data$age_group, 
        sub = "total", 
        xlab = "ages groups", 
        ylab = "days for recovering") 

female_tests <- subset(tests_data, gender == "female")
plot(female_tests$days_between_pos_and_neg ~ female_tests$age_group, 
        sub = "female", 
        xlab = "ages groups", 
        ylab = "days for recovering") 

male_tests <- subset(tests_data, gender == "male")
plot(male_tests$days_between_pos_and_neg ~ male_tests$age_group, 
        sub = "male", 
        xlab = "ages groups", 
        ylab = "days for recovering")
